        <section class="main-idea segment-opener" data-uuid="4dab1ebe641740bbaa7341b3b388c0b9">
            <article data-uuid="d05e3f130cce4e0dac57837c5ce81c92">
                <h4 data-uuid="41feec5626724806b2bb78a9a54c5747">Main Idea</h4>
                <p class="main-idea" data-uuid="bcc07d1ea46742cfa3eff5431255cc99">The issue of representation led to the Great
                    Compromise.</p>
                <h2 data-uuid="74e31121f8444875b9592263097c9571">Great Compromise</h2>
                <div class="yellow-star-yellow-bar" data-uuid="c9beeda05b184880bbbd9b209a828de2"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <h3 data-uuid="a8311863ef8c443a8f9ca3b3ceac3215">Virginia Plan</h3>
        <p data-uuid="058660d936f14f848919485046b931c2">The delegates who wanted major changes to the Articles of
            Confederation had different goals. For example, states had different ideas
            about representation, economic concerns such as tariffs, and slavery. In
            addition, delegates disagreed over how strong to make the national government. Those
            in favor of a strong national government included James Wilson, a Pennsylvania
            delegate who was known for his brilliant legal mind. </p>
        <p data-uuid="e7705ebec7f74c79954986d8504a5910">After the delegates had met for four days, Edmund Randolph
            of Virginia presented the <b><dfn title="Virginia Plan">Virginia Plan</dfn></b>, which was written by James Madison.<b> </b>The plan proposed a new
            federal constitution that would give sovereignty, or supreme power, to the
            central government. The legislature would be bicameral—made up of two
            houses, or groups of representatives—and chosen on the basis of state
            populations. Larger states would thus have more representatives than would
            smaller states. Delegates from the smaller states believed that it would give
            too much power to the larger states.</p>
